<h2>{% trans %}How to use Backstop Generator{% endtrans %}</h2>

<h3>{% trans %}1. Configure the Module{% endtrans %}</h3>
<ol>
  <li>{% trans %}Navigate to:{% endtrans %} <em>{% trans %}Configuration > Development > Backstop Generator{% endtrans %}</em> <code>/admin/config/development/backstop-generator</code></li>
  <li><strong>{% trans %}Test Domain{% endtrans %}</strong>: {% trans %}Defaults to your current site URL.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li><strong>{% trans %}Reference Domain{% endtrans %}</strong>: {% trans %}Enter the URL of the site to compare against, typically your live production site.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}Use <strong>Scenario Defaults</strong> and <strong>Profile Parameters</strong> to define default values applied to new Profiles. These can be edited later per Profile.{% endtrans %}</li>
</ol>

<h3>{% trans %}2. Configure Your Viewports{% endtrans %}</h3>
<ul>
  <li>{% trans %}Click the <strong>Viewports</strong> tab.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}Viewports are automatically created based on your theme's breakpoints.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}To add viewports for other enabled themes, use the <strong>Viewport Generator</strong>.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}Manually add a new viewport by clicking <strong>Add Viewport</strong> in the upper-right corner.{% endtrans %}</li>
</ul>

<h3>{% trans %}3. Create Your First Profile{% endtrans %}</h3>
<ol>
  <li>{% trans %}Click on the <strong>Profile</strong> tab.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}Click <strong>Add Backstop Profile</strong>.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}Provide a title and description explaining what this Profile will test.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}Select the <strong>Viewports</strong> to be used.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}Set <strong>Profile Parameters</strong> and <strong>Scenario Defaults</strong>.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>
    {% trans %}Scroll to the Scenario Generator section and configure the following:{% endtrans %}
    <ul>
      <li>{% trans %}Languages: Choose which enabled languages to test.{% endtrans %}</li>
      <li>{% trans %}Homepage: Include your siteâ€™s homepage.{% endtrans %}</li>
      <li>{% trans %}Menus: Select menus and set the <strong>Menu Depth</strong>.{% endtrans %}</li>
      <li>{% trans %}Content Types: Generate a number of random nodes per type (e.g., 5 Blog, 5 Article).{% endtrans %}</li>
      <li>{% trans %}Nodes and Paths: Use the <strong>Node Lookup</strong> field or add paths with <code>label | path</code>.{% endtrans %}</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>{% trans %}Click <strong>Save and generate scenarios</strong> to save the Profile and generate Scenarios.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}Select the Scenarios to include, then click <strong>Save</strong>.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}A BackstopJS JSON file will be generated for the Profile.{% endtrans %}</li>
</ol>

<h3>{% trans %}4. Run the Commands{% endtrans %}</h3>
<ol>
  <li>{% trans %}Go to the <strong>Commands</strong> tab.{% endtrans %}</li>
  <li>{% trans %}Copy and run the displayed commands in your terminal:{% endtrans %}
    <ul>
      <li>{% trans %}Run the <strong>reference</strong> command to generate baseline images.{% endtrans %}</li>
      <li>{% trans %}Run the <strong>test</strong> command to compare your current site with the reference version.{% endtrans %}</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

<h3>{% trans %}5. Edit Your Scenarios{% endtrans %}</h3>
<p>{% trans %}If a Scenario fails, adjust its configuration (e.g., add a selector to the{% endtrans %} <code>hideSelectors</code> {% trans %}field to hide dynamic elements). Use the text filter at the top of the Scenarios page to quickly locate specific items.{% endtrans %}</p>